i---		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
iJenkins is a free and open-source CI/CD software widely used in all		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
ikinds of scenarios. The main advantage of Jenkins is its grand		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
icollection of plugins capable of all sorts of jobs, including		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
ideploying with [SCP](https://plugins.jenkins.io/scp/) or		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i[Ansible](https://plugins.jenkins.io/ansible/), analyzing code with		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i[Cppcheck](https://plugins.jenkins.io/cppcheck/), and notifying job		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
istatus with		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i[Telegram](https://plugins.jenkins.io/telegram-notifications/) or		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i[DingTalk](https://plugins.jenkins.io/dingding-notifications/).		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
iPreviously I also used Jenkins for automation of numerous jobs, like		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
irebuilding [my Docker images](https://github.com/xddxdd/dockerfiles),		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
ideploying the blog you're visiting right now, and even		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i[auto sign-in to Genshin Impact](https://github.com/y1ndan/genshinhelper).		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
iBut Jenkins is a CI with a long history, and its predecessor Hudson		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
iwas released back in 2005. Therefore, Jenkins executes commands		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
idirectly when it comes to running jobs instead of using modern		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
iapproaches such as containers. This means that whether a CI pipeline		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
isucceeds will largely depend on the environment of the Worker host.		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
iFor example, I rented a dedicated server with higher specs. As I		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
irebuilt my whole environment, I was greeted with a number of weird		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
iissues, which took me about a week to find out and fix.		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
iIn addition, Jenkins is written in Java, hence its high memory		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
iconsumption. A Jenkins instance can take as much as 1GB RAM, which		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
imakes it impossible for a low specs server to run even the simplest		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
itasks. In addition, it's hard to use all the awesomeness of Jenkins		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
iplugins from a configuration file. A lot of plugins didn't implement		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
ithe functionality of setting parameters from a Jenkinsfile, and such		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
iplugins can only be configured one-by-one on the Jenkins webpage,		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
iwhich is a complicated and error-prone process.		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
iBy comparison, [Drone](https://www.drone.io/) the container-based CI		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
iis a relatively modern approach. Drone recommends its		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i[Docker-container-based Worker (called Runner by the Drone folks)](https://readme.drone.io/runner/docker/overview/).		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
iAs containers are used as execution environments, Drone fully exploits		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
ithe advantage of containers: consistency. As long as the container		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
iimage is consistent, you can be sure that those CI commands will be		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
iexecuted under the same environment every time, and its output should		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
ibe stable. Of course, if your script cannot run in a container by any		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
imeans, Drone also has runners for		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i[executing commands directly on host](https://readme.drone.io/runner/exec/overview/)		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
ior		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i[in a DigitalOcean cloud server](https://readme.drone.io/runner/digitalocean/overview/).		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
iDrone also has a lot of other advantages: Drone is written in Go,		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
iusing one-tenth the memory of Jenkins; Drone's configuration files are		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
iwritten in YAML or Jsonnet, unlike the special language of		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
iJenkinsfile; Although the number of		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i[Drone's plugins](http://plugins.drone.io/) is comparatively smaller		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
ito Jenkins, all of them are Docker containers and can be used from the		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
iconfiguration file.		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i|                      | Jenkins                                       | Drone                                                                      |		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i| -------------------- | --------------------------------------------- | -------------------------------------------------------------------------- |		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i| Environment          | Worker's host                                 | Your choice: Docker container, Worker's host, or DigitalOcean cloud server |		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i| Config syntax        | Special language: Jenkinsfile                 | Generic YAML/Jsonnet                                                       |		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i| Plugins              | More, 1836 (as of this is written)            | Less, 102                                                                  |		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i| Plugin config        | Web-based, some available through config file | All in config file                                                         |		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i| Programming Language | Java                                          | Go                                                                         |		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i| Memory Usage         | More, around 1GB                              | Less, around 100MB                                                         |		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i## Install Drone		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
iAs a containerized CI, Drone itself is a Docker container and is		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
iconfigured through environment variables. Drone can be connected to		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i[GitHub](https://readme.drone.io/server/provider/github/),		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i[GitLab](https://readme.drone.io/server/provider/gitlab/),		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i[Gitea](https://readme.drone.io/server/provider/gitea/) or		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i[BitBucket](https://readme.drone.io/server/provider/bitbucket-cloud/),		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
iplease refer to the linked official documents for guides. However, one		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
iDrone instance can only connect to one of them. If you are like me,		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
iwho needs CI on both GitHub and my own Gitea instance, you will need		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
itwo sets of Drone.		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
iIf you plan to use Drone for deploying, you will need some way to pass		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
iyour deployment keys to Drone. I use secret management software		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i[Vault](https://www.vaultproject.io/),		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i[with official support from Drone](https://docs.drone.io/secret/external/vault/).		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
iOf course, you can simply store your secrets in Drone, but not through		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
iits web UI. You must		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i[use Drone's command-line tool for that](https://readme.drone.io/secret/).		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
